USA: Repetition is Mother of Wisdom
It is almost strange with which student eagerness Barack Obama, the president with his reputation of the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor on the Afghanistan question, which he himself considered to be the dumbest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly awaited Afghanistan doctrine, it turned out that he wrote it off three years ago via the copy paper from the Bush Iraq scenario.
Not only did he use the phrase "as in Iraq" several times in the text, he even used the name of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "New Forward Way" without fidgeting.
Three years ago, he himself criticized the Bush idea of sending out fresh contingents of troops in Iraq, plagued by the civil war, as "irresponsible and in its consequences a carastrophic decision".
The following months, however, showed that the Bush strategy, based on military recommendations, was the only possible and very successful one, so far, that the news about Iraq no longer speaks at all.
This did not improve Bush’s reputation, for objectively he left his successor with a much more appreciative starting point than was expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
He was again asked by the military to increase the contingent of troops, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghanistan operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordination habits, strongly criticized the timid shooters in the White House.
