Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted in favour of a construction ban for minarets and the concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, has written a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated — and integrated — into one of the most declaredly secularized societies in Europe.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French Don't Love Headscarves" (2006), an elegant and highly argued study of an issue that divided and occupied the country for a decade and a half and whose effects can still be perceived today.
Bowen's latest book offers a broader and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media are saying about Islam in France, but what is really happening in the field.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes that now offer 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it, "Islamic freedom".
He is a good listener, he gives debates between teachers and students about the questions they are most concerned about.
Should a Muslim marry (or both) in a mosque or town hall?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it permissible for a Muslim to use an interest-based banking system to get a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profane matters, he claims, that make up daily life, quite unlike the political dramas that occupy the media.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arab-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They do not have all the arguments on their side.
Conservatives are suspicious of the idea of French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists that Bowen questioned are mostly divided with their Salafi counterparts – advocates of purist Sunni Islam, which is associated with Saudi Arabia – which nowadays show a small but influential presence among Europe's Muslims.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who so passionately guard the separation of church and state) feel truly committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may experience harsher treatment than Catholics, Protestants, and Jews, who in turn had to make their historical compromise with secular Republicanism.
He is more likely to recognize a "increase of the value screws" than a growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, one is inclined to say "Yes, but not yet".
