The news of the arrest was first reported by the New York Times on Friday night.
The new US policy places great value on the fact that the United States will provide a return if the Cuban government takes concrete steps in this direction, such as the release of political prisoners and the creation of more room for opposition.
Mobile phones and notebooks are legal in Cuba, although they are new and sought after products in a country where the average salary of a government employee is $15 a month.
The Cuban government has only allowed ordinary citizens to buy a mobile phone since this year; they are used primarily for sending text messages, as a 15-minute telephone call would cost a daily wage.
Internet usage on the island is extremely restricted.
It is available in expensive hotels and there for foreign visitors and at some government offices, such as universities.
Cubans who want to log in often have to report their names to the government.
Access to many websites is restricted.
In Cuba, the arrest of an American is rare.
Most of the few U.S. citizens in prison in Cuba are behind bars for crimes such as drug smuggling, said Gloria Berbena, the press spokesperson for the U.S. interest representation in Havana.
Berbena said she couldn't give any more information about the arrest.
The arrest and detention are clearly wrong.
An activity that would be legal in any other free society - the delivery of free mobile phones - is a crime in Cuba, said Jose Miguel Vivarco, head of the American section of the "Human Rights Watch" group, who recently published a hard report on freedom in Cuba entitled "New Castro, Same Cuba", an allusion to the appointment of Raul Castro as leader of the country, replacing the sick older brother Fidel.
