Established in the country's constitution in 1978, China's one-child policy is likely to be the most controversial order introduced by the ruling Communist Party to this day.
Married couples who violate this policy have to face enormous fines -- up to three times their annual salary in some regions -- and discrimination at their workplace.
Chinese state representatives have attributed it to this policy that the critical use of natural land resources could be avoided, whereas human rights representatives have condemned abuses in the enforcement of politics.
In rural areas, some officials have forced pregnant women who have already had a child to abort.
Many couples had also had sex selective abortions, resulting in an unnaturally high relationship between men and women.
In recent years, government representatives for the population have gradually weakened their attitude towards one-child policies.
In 2004, they allowed more exceptions to the rule -- including city dwellers, members of ethnic minorities, and cases where both husband and wife were single children -- and in 2007, the tone of many tough slogans was softened.
Qiao Xiaochun, a professor at Beijing University's Department of Population Research, said that government officials have recently even discussed more radical changes, such as allowing couples to have two children with one partner as an only child.
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to launch an aggressive campaign to promote more births in July.
Posters instructing families to have only one child were replaced almost overnight by guidelines describing in detail who is eligible for a second child and how to apply for permission.
The city administration has sent out municipal employees and volunteers for family planning to visit couples at home and put leaflets under the doors.
She also asked to provide psychological and financial advice to those who have more than one child.
The response was not very encouraging, said family planning representatives.
Disappointing reaction
Although officials from a rural small town in the outdoor areas of Shanghai said that an upswing can be seen in the applications of couples who want a second child after the start of the campaign, the urban districts do not report any change.
The municipality of Huinan with a population of 115,000 still receives only four to five applications per month as an example.
Disappointed Shanghai officials say that despite the campaign, the expected number of births in the city in 2010 will still be around 165,000 -- slightly higher than in 2009, but lower than in 2008.
Feng Juying, head of the Family Planning Committee of Caolu Township in Shanghai, said that financial considerations are probably the main reason why many people don't want to have children anymore.
