Yang Jiawei, 27, and his wife, Liu Juanjuan, 26, said that they would like to have two children and that they would be legally allowed to do so.
But, like many Chinese people, they have only a minor health and life insurance policy from the government.
Without a social network, they say, this decision would be irresponsible.
People in the West misjudge one-child politics as a human rights issue, said Yang, a civil engineer whose wife is pregnant with her first child in the seventh month.
Yes, we're being robbed of the opportunity to have more than one child.
But the problem is not simply a policy.
The problem is money.
Other couples give psychological reasons for their hesitation.
Wang, the HR manager, said she only wanted a child because she was also an only child. "We were the center of the family and used to everyone taking care of us.
We are not used to taking care of others and don't really want this."
Chen Zijian, a 42-year-old who owns a translation company, said it bluntly.
For middle-class parents with a double career, through which the birth rate decreases, he said, it revolves around being successful and for that one has to be selfish.
The age group of today's 20- to 39-year-olds grew up to see their parents fight during the early days of the Chinese capitalism experiment and they do not want such a life for themselves, he said.
Even a single child, he said, places huge demands on the time of parents.
