We don't want to make too many sacrifices.
UN Group designs emission reduction plan
The UN-sponsored climate conference -- which has so far been characterized by wild poses and mutual accusations -- has once again set a focus on Friday with the publication of a document that records an ambitious reduction in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with the industrial nations shouldering the greatest burdens in the near future.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, has both identified the remaining obstacles and shown the way forward.
But it was seen as an important step forward in a negotiation that will run out of time, with more than 100 top politicians from all over the world arriving in Copenhagen next week.
The text, formulated by a specially created UN working group, is silent about the money that rich countries should give to poor countries so that they can cope with global warming in the short and long term.
It also provides a range of options for key issues, including how industrialised and large emerging economies can limit their carbon emissions and how high the upper limit of global temperature rise that policy makers would support.
The process is given great flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative of the Sierra Club in Washington.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, has summarized a 180-page negotiation text to focus on what UN leaders, Yvo de Boer, called "the big picture".
It shows the outline of a possible agreement in which developed countries would jointly reduce their emissions by 25 to 45 percent by 2020, compared to the 1990 limit values, while larger developing countries would reduce their emissions by 15 to 30 percent in the same period.
Together, countries could reduce emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Community has also given a boost to the talks on Friday through its commitment to provide $3.6 billion per year over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the effects of climate change - from mastering floods and droughts to avoiding deforestation.
Friday nevertheless brought the same verbal fireworks that had determined the talks last week.
The US climate special representative Todd Stern has rejected formulations calling for binding reductions in greenhouse gas emissions for industrialised countries, compared to voluntary reductions for larger emerging economies, if these are not financed by developed countries.
This train announced that the Obama administration was driving a tougher line with China than representatives of the Bush administration less than two years ago.
The United States will not sign an agreement without major emerging economies standing up and taking action, says Stern, who also complained that the text does not go far enough to ensure that the reductions could also be confirmed by outsiders.
Stern gave his statement an hour after the statement of the Chinese Deputy Foreign Minister He Yafei, which said that the leading American climate negotiator either lacked "reason" or it was "highly irresponsible" of him that he said earlier this week that the United States would not financially help China to cope with global warming.
The fact that the future economic march of the major world powers is at stake has opened fault lines both within the industrialized nations and between the industrialized nations and the emerging economies.
The current struggle is about saving individual economies as well as saving the planet, with China and the United States fighting for their commitments, while poorer countries claim that the two dozen most influential countries would ignore the scientific need to take bolder action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said that it was not surprising that the great powers were fighting for who should bear the costs of curbing greenhouse gas emissions, as even affected countries have become more aggressive in calling the countries with very high greenhouse gas emissions to account for their actions.
This is clearly a game from which a new economic dominance will develop, according to Ulate, who is also working as a regional climate change consultant for Conservation International in Mexico and Central America.
Some of the countries most exposed to the effects of climate change stated that they would continue to fight for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although the leaders say that the talks will lead to a political agreement at best.
The Alliance of Small Island States, with 43 members, presented a 24-page draft treaty early on Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads the international climate negotiations for the European Commission, said that the offensive of the small island states "puts political pressure on the entire political process" partly because they are now united and demand action from emerging countries, such as China and India.
The talks received a new urgency when the delegates focused on the fact that most of the outstanding issues had to be resolved before the leaders arrived to reach an agreement.
High-ranking representatives, such as Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Vice Minister, escaped their planes and raced through the Bella Center corridors to meetings behind closed doors and press conferences to stake claims that will be negotiated over the next week.
The pure extent of the meeting -- 13,000 people go in and out every day at the convention center, guitar-playing activists do night shows, making fun of the countries that they think are betraying and selling, and contract drafts are hand-to-hand instead of email -- is already a challenge.
The intensity is just building up: almost all the important ministers are here now and from Wednesday 60 leaders will be in Copenhagen.
We come to the Oberliga, said Carlos Manuel Rodriguez, Vice President for Global Politics of the Organization Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
