Affaire Liliane Bettencourt : François-Marie Banier condemned for exploitation of weakness
On Friday, the Nanterre Court of Justice decided to judge the artist François-Marie Banier in order to determine whether, as the daughter of the billionaire Liliane Bettencourt claims, he has exploited a weak moment of the eighty-year-olds to steal part of their property.
The 62-year-old photographer, who is known for his star photographs, will have to answer for the exploitation of weakness in court on 15 and 16 April 2010, a crime punishable by a maximum imprisonment of three years and a fine of 375,000 euros.
This decision means that there will indeed be a process in this affair worthy of the saga of one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter are torn apart and at the same time the reins of the cosmetics empire L'Oréal are in their hands.
However, the 15th Trial Chamber also ordered a medical examination of the 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt, which is conducted jointly by three doctors.
The heiress and principal shareholder of L'Oréal has so far refused to submit to such an investigation, especially not under the conditions submitted by the Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office during the investigation.
The doctors appointed on Friday will present a report before 10 March 2010 in which you will make clear whether and at what times Liliane Bettencourt may have been in a state of weakness.
I think she's going to go through these tests.
I will talk to her, explained the lawyer of Mrs. Bettencourt, Me Georges Kiejman, after the trial.
As regards the lawyer of Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers, Me Olivier Metzner, he is very pleased with the court's decision.
This is an excellent news (...). The report will prove that he (Banier) has manipulated this old lady, whom one must protect, he affirmed.
For two years now, Liliane Bettencourt's only daughter has initiated a criminal lawsuit against François-Marie Banier, photographer and all-round artist, accusing him of having exploited her mother's weakness for years in order to steal donations of a total of one billion euros in the form of bank cheques, insurance policies or paintings.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt had always disproved that she had been manipulated by the photographer, whom she regards as a long-time friend.
Although the court would have to examine the admissibility of the lawsuit initiated by Ms Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers' plaidoyers led to a large family debacle on Friday.
For example, Liliane Bettencourt's lawyer relied on three letters sent by his client to her notary (1999, 2003 and 2005), in which she wrote that she distrusted Françoise Bettencourt-Meyer's husband.
