The Nanterre Public Prosecutor's Office is again of the opinion that the applicant had no right to react in this way, especially because in recent days a guardian judge has refused to initiate a judicial protection procedure against her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "is fully legal, is not protected and has no guardian.
Nobody has the right to act in their place," said the prosecutor's representative, Marie-Christine Daubigney.
The Court of First Instance has now decided to give a judgment after the procedure for the admissibility of Ms Bettencourt-Meyers has taken place.
Manager revolution or the end of the Strategic Early Enlightenment?
If nothing changes in the leadership of the great French companies, our struggle for the development of economic intelligence has been in vain ...
For over a decade, the attitude of the management of large companies in terms of its employees, said the position of the companies vis-à-vis the consumer prior to the marketing revolution: It is intended for the personnel to join "values" destined to impose the best as it used to be on the consumer products designed by the technicians in the factory.
By putting the customer at the center of companies, the marketing revolution has given the strategies of conquering the markets in the place ... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products separately factors preferences of customers again regularly!
Demobilization of employees can lead to fatal demoralisation.
The suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of a much larger phenomenon that affects employees in particular.
This demobilization has a negative impact on the development of all the company's intellectual functions, especially those of R&Eand, which is even more crucial, those of economic intelligence.
In fact, IE (Intelligence Economique = Economic Intelligence) demands "a proactive approach and a forward-looking view from all parties involved"; it claims from the employees a commitment to which the instructions of authoritarian management completely contradict.
That is why we are calling for an operational revolution, which would consist in placing the employees in the center of the company's concerns on an equal footing with the customers.
The very conditional benefits of internal opinion polls
Will the internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire submitted by Orange to its wage earners, stimulate this revolution in terms of management practice?
I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I've been able to see that, given a new situation, after many detours, the whole structure finally comes to do, as a matter of priority, what it has always done.
Also because authoritarianism - one of the pathologies of power - increases in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
And finally, because most leaders have a much simplified idea of human behavior.
Their interpretation of psychology is mechanistic from the major engineering schools.
Through intellectual comfort, they adopt the old behaviorist theory, recently reactivated by the American "neurosciences" and unknowingly widely spread by research institutes and the media.
Thus, and by suggesting that it is possible to use the "sic" to engage employees, a recent Le Figaro.fr survey by Ipsos encourages executives in an attitude towards a mechanistic control system that is unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure the mobilisation factors
Instead, an operational revolution necessary for the smooth functioning of modern companies requires the adoption of a definitive view of human behaviour.
It consists of integrating a basic protocol into any consideration or practice of governance: for wage earners, commitment to the enterprise is only possible if it clearly appears to be a means of realizing part of their dreams, ambition and intentions.
At the moment only the studies from the multifunctional analysis take on this concept of motivation of the employees.
These studies have shown that they assess their company on the basis of a given doxa that allows them to estimate what it offers them to achieve their life goals through their perceived image of the company.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of these mobilization factors, the managers of the companies can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and place their human resource management in the right place again.
In this way, they create a fertile soil that is favourable for the coordinated development of robust and efficient economic intelligence.
The Oslo speech: the "just war" brings praise to Obama from the right
The American Right welcomed Barack Obama's speech in Oslo on Friday evening and was pleased that the Nobel Peace Prize 2009 defended the concept of "just war" against the enemies of the United States.
The conservatives who mocked the awarding of the prize to Obama on October 9 applauded the President's speech this time, following the example of the former Vice-Presidentship candidate in the 2008 elections, Sarah Palin.
