Drivers: Three marathons for an agreement to secure the supply for Christmas
After a three-week negotiation marathon, the unions of the Road Association and the TLF - the only employers' organization that remained until the end - reached an agreement on Friday evening that would put an end to the strike order and the impending severe shortage of supplies at Christmas.
At the signature meeting on Friday evening, the Secretary of State for Transport, Dominique Bussereau, "welcomed" the agreement which was launched on Wednesday morning after several weeks of negotiations.
After a second night of negotiations, the negotiators parted early on Friday morning in the hope of signing the agreement quickly in the late morning.
And even though the three employers' associations (FNTR, Unostra and OTRE) had left the meeting furiously.
However, more than six hours passed from the beginning of the meeting at 11:00 a.m. to the conclusion of the agreement and the agreement was not signed until 18:00 p.m.
The conflict "had caused a lot of damage to the companies" and "it was to be feared that it would affect the holidays at the end of the year", said Bussereau.
The agreement provides for a 4% increase in wages for the lowest wages (local and regional road transport) and 2.9% for the highest wage groups (international transport).
The hourly rate for workers with the lowest wages thus rises from EUR 8.72 to EUR 9.06.
"That's not much, but we'll start small," says Patrice Clos (FO).
Activists are now being instructed not to block the supply centres.
"However, there will probably always be some unruly people who are not satisfied with the agreement," he adds.
TLF president Philippe Grillot spoke of a "good agreement", although it was "difficult to grant these wage increases in the face of international competition".
