"This agreement is based on common sense and respect for employees," said Maxime Dumont (CFDT), while Thierry Douine (CFTC) spoke of "a historic agreement".
Richard Jaubert (CGT) spoke about "an acceptable compromise".
The agreement also provides for a 3% increase in travel costs and the maintenance of the overall budget for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will in particular make it possible to address the issue of 13th monthly salary and the modernisation of collective agreements.
M. Bussereau recalled that "the reduction of employers' taxes of EUR 100 million" was the subject of an amendment by the government to the bill for the adjusted finances for 2009, which was adopted by the National Assembly on the night of Thursday to Friday.
The government demands "an identical" vote from the Senate.
The signature of the TLF allows the agreement to apply first to the companies affiliated to this organisation and then, if extended by the Minister of Labour, to the entire profession.
This will be the case "in no time", Bussereau assures.
The opposition of employers' associations can only delay the procedure.
FNTR denounced "fraudy trade" because the EUR 100 million "had already been promised to the sector to compensate for some of the carbon tax".
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate as soon as possible, but not on the basis of a joint analysis, but in order not to upset the goose eaters on the approaching Christmas days, the Unostra complains.
For the Otre association, the agreement threatens "to dig a grave for small and medium-sized enterprises in the industry in the next 12 months".
