Turkish Constitutional Court dissolves pro-Kurdish party. Decision with serious consequences
On Friday, the Turkish Constitutional Court announced the dissolution of the country's main pro-Kurdish party, a decision followed immediately by furious demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision threatens to make the work of the government enormously difficult, which is trying to reach out to the Kurdish community to put an end to the conflicts that have been going on for 25 years.
The "Party for a Democratic Society" (DTP) was dissolved as it had become a "place for activities detrimental to the independence of the state and its indivisible unity", according to the President of the Constitutional Court Hasim Kiliç four days after the decision to the press.
According to Kiliç, the decision would have been taken unanimously by 11 judges, with a majority of seven votes being required to impose the dissolution. Furthermore, he pointed out that 37 of the party’s leaders, including the chairman Ahmet Türk and the parliamentarian Aysel Tugluk, were excluded from political action for a period of five years.
The judge also announced the waiver of parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, as well as the confiscation of the Party's property.
The DTP now has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Before the verdict, the party leaders said that parliamentarians would rather leave Parliament than sit like non-partisan parliamentarians.
The decision was followed by a trial initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Turkish Federal Court Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya. He accused the DTP of following the "wisdoms" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which is regarded by Ankara and numerous other countries as a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has "no connection" to the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate.
The verdict of the Constitutional Court intercedes with the government, which seeks to meet the Kurdish community and propose a series of measures to strengthen the rights of the Kurds, in order to make the support of the PKK by the Kurds run out and to put an end to the conflicts.
The leaders of the DTP affirm that a resolution could lead to a re-emergence of tensions in South-East Anatolia, where numerous demonstrations against the prison conditions of PKK chief Abdullah Öcalan had led to clashes with the police in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of the court, thousands of demonstrators have gathered in front of the DTP premises in the megacity of Diyarbakir in the southeast, which is predominantly populated by Kurds.
The police used tear gas grenades and water cannons when the demonstrators started throwing molotov cocktails and stones.
Hundreds of people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Türk assumed that the court's decision "will deepen despair even further".
"Turkey cannot resolve this (Kurdish, editorial note) question on the basis of a party's ban," he explained to the press.
The government, consisting of a party that emerged from the Islamist movement, also regretted the decision.
"We oppose the closure of the parties on principle.
This does not solve the problems," said Minister Taner Yildiz.
"This decision is a torpedoing of the democratic opening promoted by the government," said the political market observer Ahmet Island.
"You can obviously get ready for a reaction from the PKK," he adds.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for an attack that killed seven soldiers in northern Turkey three days earlier, one of the most brutal attacks in recent months.
