The cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50-metre-large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it wouldn't be anything special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body traits, reports Sterling Nesbitt from the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in the journal Science of Thursday.
About 215 million years ago, the animal lived in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, which is unprecedented for triassic deposits, team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History reports.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
In the course of the excavation, they collected the remains of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino's early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaur fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, mostly only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these primordial dinos is usually controversial.
For example, the experts discuss when the lizards split into their three main development lines: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the four-legged sauropods known as "long necks" and their relatives, and the plants-eating Ornithischia (bird-basin dinosaurs), which included the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus, for example.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is an original theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced properties, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air bags, as did the descendants of the Theropods, the birds.
Thanks to the air bags, birds' breathing is more efficient than mammals' breathing.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partly filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropode with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the giant sauropods later also had air bags and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards appeared there for the first time.
According to this, the three development lines separated early and spread from South America over all parts of the world, which then formed a single land mass as a supercontinent of Pangäa.
This is supported by the fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not very closely related theropods.
The researchers argue that the three cannot be descended from a common immigrant ancestor.
We believe there were at least three migratory waves to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
In his opinion, a distorted picture could arise, because in South America many primitive dinosaur fossils have simply been preserved, while on other continents hardly anything can be found.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare sideline of the reptile trunk to the dominant land vertebrates of the Earth's Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Triassic the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and flight dinosaurs and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread all over the world and developed many new species, while the relationship on the border from the Triassic to the Jura died out.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There could have been a mass death that the dinosaurs happened to survive, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to bloom, which had also developed in the Triassic, and since then, a shadow existence has lasted: the mammals.
