New Silicon Valley
For many years it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenograd, one of the ten districts of the capital Moscow, was a heavily guarded site for secret military research in the Soviet Union.
Today, the municipality with its 216 000 inhabitants, 37 kilometers from Moscow center, is considered as the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Important research and production sites for micro- and nanoelectronics are located here.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have established contacts with the Frankfurt Science Centre Riedberg - with the university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Centre (FIZ).
There were several mutual visits and on Wednesday Selenograd and Riedberg signed a "Protocol on closer cooperation" in Frankfurt.
The Moscow Deputy Mayor Yuri Rosljak and Prefect Anatoly Smirnov of Selenograd headed the Russian delegation, and Edwin Schwarz, the planning officer for Frankfurt, signed.
In 2010, representatives of the FIZ and small and medium-sized companies of the scientific research focus will travel to Selenograd for a seminar.
Scientific exchange
It is about a continuous scientific exchange.
But it is also about economic relations.
FIZ companies will be able to gain a foothold in the growing Russian market.
Conversely, Russian science companies want to win contracts in Germany.
Selenograd is the seat of major Russian research institutes and companies.
These include the Moscow Institute of Electron Technology, the major companies Sitronics and Rossijskaya Elektronika.
The municipality was founded in 1958 as a so-called "socialist planning city" for armament research.
Selenograd (literally "Grünstadt") received its name from the wooded hilly landscape in which the research facilities are embedded.
Stuttgart brake block
