Dream worlds
Some see images in awake condition and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
The boundaries between imagination and reality become blurred not only in the mentally ill and in the drug rush.
As long as it happens in sleep, everything's fine.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we are allowed to indulge uninhibited in the wildest ideas and imaginations.
However, those who experience dreamlike conditions in growth, see and hear things that others do not see or hear, are usually considered crazy or drug addicted in the modern Western world, at least as a weirdo.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the case of the mentally ill or in the drug rush.
Our imagination is to blame: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures or write novels sometimes make the boundaries between dream, delusion and reality blur.
Dream-like altered waking consciousness states can occur in various forms, in the best case we call them visions, in the worst case delusion.
Although triggers and effects may differ, the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the drug experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castaneda, shamanic states of Rapture, psychosis and hallucinations can be traced back to similar processes.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal messenger substances of the brain - especially dopamine, noradrenaline, serotonin and acetylcholine - is derailed and the interaction of different brain parts is disturbed.
Complex hallucinations and delusional thoughts occur very often during schizophrenic psychosis.
Gravity has no power over him
The connection between delusion and dream has been occupied by philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle saw hallucinations as a form of the dream in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great similarity of madness with dream states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all inconsistencies, delusions, illusions of such."
