It was triggered by LSD.
His diagnosis is schizoaffective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, he takes medications for depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis, I have experienced the worst fear and deepest despair, he says.
The illusions are a cruel reality
About one percent of the population suffers from schizophrenia at least once in their lives, and in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, sufferers can usually no longer distinguish between the inner and outer worlds, they get into an overexcited state that can lead to hallucinations, megalomania, relationship or persecution.
Voice listening is particularly common - voices that command, comment or dialogue.
Even optical hallucinations are not uncommon.
The affected person is no longer able to separate important things from unimportant things, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like the dream, psychosis opens the locks to a flood of ideas and fantasies that come from deeper layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, senior physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the centre of the event, everything has a meaning directed at it.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, he is overwhelmed by the events, like in a dream, and he cannot actively shape them.
Schizophrenic patients therefore often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
They are not usually able to compare reality, the illusions are cruel reality, waking up is excluded.
Once in a lifetime to have experienced a hallucination
Unlike in the dream, Fuchs says, "but the sensual and spatial structure of reality, which is perceived in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved."
The delusional thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place within a real framework.
Why exactly our brain beats caprioles, researchers are still puzzled.
Exceptions can lead to a short-term loss of reality in every human being, says Fuchs.
But not everyone will develop psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but twin studies have shown that genes are not the only determining factors.
Researchers assume that there are minimal brain damage in those affected.
We suspect that neuronal maturation of the brain is disrupted at an early stage of development by a mother’s viral disease during pregnancy, for example, explains Fuchs.
But it remains a mystery how the disorder of the neural system comes about, which is not manifesting for many years at first.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can trigger a psychosis if the disposition is present.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis as they interfere with the transmitter system.
When our brains run hot
The crazy thing is, psychotics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others spend money on drugs to get them, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Whether false images are perceived as pleasant or unpleasant is often only a question of viewpoint.
For ten years, Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and delusions, and last year he evaluated his findings in the book "The Irreal World in Our Head".
Hallucinations are among the typical side effects of psychosis, but also of astoundingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline or depression, these often include diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer's disease and cranial brain trauma.
Surprisingly, even the brain of healthy people is hallucinated under certain conditions.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memory contents that are normally held back.
They arise when brain areas in which sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or too little inhibited; when our brain is running hot or even when stimulation is missing.
Drugs can cause this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
