A normal girl, actually.
If it weren't for the pictures and voices.
During the break it can happen that a shaky boy with long, dark hair appeals to it.
When it answers him, the classmates look surprised - no one else sees or hears this boy.
They think the shy girl is a spun daydreamer, but Sarah K. doesn't dream, she knows.
She is awake, she hears and sees this boy, just as she hears and sees the girl in the bank next to her.
She can even feel his presence, at least for moments.
A pleasant feeling is that she likes the boy.
Am I crazy?, she sometimes wonders.
But she knows that this boy and the other illusions are not real and disappear again.
At night, the appearances are usually frightening
Often the illusions are also a burden.
When she is sitting in the classroom, she sometimes cannot follow the teaching material, because the teacher is introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, while he is explaining mathematical equations for all the others, both hearingly and visibly, on the board.
At night, the apparitions are usually frightening.
When she waits in her dark room for sleep, which is far too rare and far too late, she often cannot tell whether she is awake or already dreaming, whether the pictures she sees are the faces or the girl with the bleeding cuts on her arms and legs, in front of her open or closed eyes.
Leave me alone, she screams at the figures.
Parents and friends don't tell her about it, they think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed her Abitur last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she made contact with the psychologist box on the Internet, she knows she's not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of despair
If someone is socially isolated or suffers from excitement, he is most likely to have hallucinations after a while, says Kasten.
I suppose the brain is then underworked and provides its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at the age of 13 that the man she calls Papa has not been her biological father since she could think.
Since the same brain areas are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real impressions and noises, it is difficult for people like Sarah K. to distinguish between illusions and reality. "Every experience," says Kasten, "takes place in the brain, the reality is there.
Hallucinations are also images that create the brain, which is why they work so real."
Even nightly dream pictures treat caste as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of an acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their delusions as unreal.
Therefore, Kasten advises his patients to value hallucinations as a special ability.
Border State between Dream and Hallucination
Unfortunately, in our overly mind-centered world, imaginary experiences are mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Department of Psychiatry and Psychotherapy at the Florence Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a serious, painful illness, but it also contains positive, creative - delusion is also a work of art out of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has explored the so-called oneiroid experience form, a special form of dream-like altered waking consciousness.
Oneiroids are highly complex, detailed quasi-dreams, which the experiencer considers real and which he cannot distinguish from the state of waking even in hindsight.
The oneironoid state of consciousness arises in trauma or disease-related extreme situations, for example in polyradiculitis patients who experience motor paralysis with full consciousness.
When a person is threatened with loss of self and world, for example, by persistent, complete immobility of movement, he replaces the life-threatening real situation with his own imaginary world, which is decoupled from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
A kind of borderline between dream and hallucination.
Since overcoming a situation in reality is not possible, a world change takes place, but the real situation is visualized in imagination.
An intensive form of sense and meaning in a situation that is in itself unbearable, which enables us humans to create our own ability not to sink into a nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
The Zurich art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his oneiroid experiences in his book "Herzwechsel" as a rescue action of the soul.
He is 49 years old when his consciousness travels for days after a heart valve operation followed by a heart transplant, while his body in the intensive care unit is doomed to motionlessness.
Claussen dives into a self-created world, visits strange times and places: he experiences himself as a bedridden, old man, on board a train sanatorium, a robot watches over his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among nobles who make drugs from blood.
Moved by a Greek on a motorcycle to his home country, he surfs with his hospital bed in the firn snow of the Alps and meets a Korean mafioso.
He is fully absorbed in the imaginary event, everything is real, even later in memory.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dream is a different state, he describes his experience.
In contrast, the memories from mental travels are still overly clear to me after years and in minor details.
Clearer and more intense even than really experienced.
The intensity of this experience bursts the horizon of our other life-worldly experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Ultimately, oneiroids, psychoses, hallucinations and drug rush show how fragile our inner images of outer reality are in the wake.
Any change in the state of consciousness, sums up the psychologist caste, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that can also be enriching.
