75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially among younger women who want to have children.
This is the result of the study "Fruitability and career of women in Spain" carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute for Women.
The survey of 9,737 women aged between 15 and 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75% of working women see their career opportunities in the labour market as limited due to their motherhood.
The study reveals that there are major differences in the decision to start a family and in the number of children, depending on whether women work or not and, if so, what kind of occupation they do.
Those of them who do not do any other work outside the house, work only half-day or have no fixed employment contract are more likely to be mothers and have more children.
In contrast, women with fixed employment, especially in the public sector, postpone the establishment of a family and motherhood and therefore have fewer children.
"Women in the 35-49 age group with a fixed job only receive their first child on average 3.7 years after moving together, a figure which increases to 4.1 years for women with a fixed job who have taken longer to achieve this and who have brought about their moving together and the first child much later.
In addition, the type of work has a great influence on motherhood, albeit less than the calendar on conceptional readiness," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that must be taken into account in the age of women in marriage and the first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of education, the higher the age at the time of marriage and the first child.
This difference could also be found in women of the same age.
For example, women in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, depending on whether they only have a primary or higher education, were, on average, mothers for the first time with 25.1 or 32.1 respectively.
There is also another difference between women, depending on their level of education.
While the women with the main degree already get married and have their first child before their first permanent employment, the women with a middle or high school degree do exactly the other way around and first look for a permanent employment and get married after that and then get their first child, Delgado notes.
