The sale of small trucks is increasing again
After almost two years, the car market for vans finally begins to see some light at the end of the dark tunnel.
The 9,425 vehicles registered in Spain in November represent an increase of 12.6% in relation to 2008, and, more importantly, they are the first increase after 22 consecutive months, with a steady decline, according to the figures presented by the manufacturer association Anfac and the car dealer association Ganvam.
However, these good figures are currently only available with great caution, as the reference data used for the comparison are from November 2008, which was a particularly bad year of sale with a decrease of 60% compared to the previous year.
However, it must be borne in mind that, apart from the increase in the last month, the total registrations for these 11 months are still 40% below the sales figures for the previous financial year.
A total of 95,853 vehicles have been sold since January, but this figure includes all the vehicles that make up the van market: derivatives of passenger cars, pick-ups, vans, small vans and lighter vans/carts.
Furthermore, there are still the same storm clouds in the sky, which most affect the demand, because even if some of the vehicles are purchased by private individuals, most of the sales go to small and medium-sized enterprises, which in almost 100 % of all cases make the purchase with a third party financing.
For example, to these restrictions, which are the result of the banks' closed-off money tap, one has to include other factors, such as the increase in the unemployment rate or the persistence of the bad economic situation.
